 10  # Local homeomorphisms
 11  
 12  This file defines homeomorphisms between open subsets of topological spaces. An element `e` of
 13  `local_homeomorph α β` is an extension of `local_equiv α β`, i.e., it is a pair of functions
 14  `e.to_fun` and `e.inv_fun`, inverse of each other on the sets `e.source` and `e.target`.
 15  Additionally, we require that these sets are open, and that the functions are continuous on them.
 16  Equivalently, they are homeomorphisms there.
 17  
 18  Contrary to equivs, we do not register the coercion to functions and we use explicitly to_fun and
 19  inv_fun: coercions create unification problems for manifolds.
 20  
 21  ## Main definitions
 22  
 23  `homeomorph.to_local_homeomorph`: associating a local homeomorphism to a homeomorphism, with
 24                                    source = target = univ
 25  `local_homeomorph.symm`  : the inverse of a local homeomorphism
 26  `local_homeomorph.trans` : the composition of two local homeomorphisms
 27  `local_homeomorph.refl`  : the identity local homeomorphism
 28  `local_homeomorph.of_set`: the identity on a set `s`
 29  `eq_on_source`           : equivalence relation describing the "right" notion of equality for local
 30                             homeomorphisms
 31  
 32  ## Implementation notes
 33  
 34  Most statements are copied from their local_equiv versions, although some care is required
 35  especially when restricting to subsets, as these should be open subsets.
 36  
 37  For design notes, see `local_equiv.lean`.
 38  -/

 77  sufficient to have equal to_fun and source, as this only determines inv_fun on the target. This
 78  would only be true for a weaker notion of equality, arguably the right one, called `eq_on_source`. -/
